subsection.p:
A nonzero vector \mathbf v is an eigenvector of A if

  \boxed{
  A\mathbf v=\lambda \mathbf v
  }

for some scalar \lambda.

p.md:
\begin{array}{c|c}
\lambda \amp \text{Effect on eigenvector direction} \\ \hline
\lambda\gt1 \amp \text{stretch}\\
0\lt\lambda\lt1 \amp \text{shrink}\\
\lambda\lt0 \amp \text{reverse direction and scale}\\
\lambda=0 \amp \text{collapse to zero}
\end{array}

subsection.p:
Eigenvalues are the roots of

  \boxed{
  p(\lambda)=0.
  }

If

  A=
  \begin{pmatrix}
  a\amp b\\
  c\amp d
  \end{pmatrix},

then

  \boxed{
  \operatorname{tr}(A)=a+d
  }

and

  \boxed{
  \det(A)=ad-bc.
  }

The characteristic equation can be written as

  \boxed{
  \lambda^2-\operatorname{tr}(A)\lambda+\det(A)=0.
  }

For each eigenvalue \lambda, solve

  \boxed{
  (A-\lambda I)\mathbf v=\mathbf 0.
  }

Remember:

  \boxed{
  \mathbf v\ne\mathbf 0.
  }

The zero vector is never called an eigenvector.

Let

  \boxed{
  D=
  \begin{pmatrix}
  \lambda_1\amp0\amp\cdots\amp0\\
  0\amp\lambda_2\amp\cdots\amp0\\
  \vdots\amp\vdots\amp\ddots\amp\vdots\\
  0\amp0\amp\cdots\amp\lambda_n
  \end{pmatrix}.
  }

Then

  \boxed{
  A=PDP^{-1}.
  }

If

  A=PDP^{-1},

then

  \boxed{
  A^k=PD^kP^{-1}.
  }

For a diagonal matrix,

  \boxed{
  D^k=
  \begin{pmatrix}
  \lambda_1^k\amp0\amp\cdots\amp0\\
  0\amp\lambda_2^k\amp\cdots\amp0\\
  \vdots\amp\vdots\amp\ddots\amp\vdots\\
  0\amp0\amp\cdots\amp\lambda_n^k
  \end{pmatrix}.
  }

If

  A^T=A,

then:

  \begin{array}{ll}
  1. \amp \text{All eigenvalues of }A\text{ are real.}\\[1mm]
  2. \amp \text{Eigenvectors for different eigenvalues are orthogonal.}\\[1mm]
  3. \amp A\text{ has an orthonormal eigenbasis.}
  \end{array}

Thus a symmetric matrix can be written as

  \boxed{
  A=QDQ^T,
  }

where Q is orthogonal:

  \boxed{
  Q^TQ=I.
  }
